{{Infobox ethnic group |group= Chhipa |image=‘Chipi (or chimba), a cloth printer - Tashrih al-aqvam (1825), f.260v - BL Add. 27255.jpg |caption=Chhipa, a cloth printer from ''Tashrih al-aqvam'' (1825) |popplace = Nepal,<ref name=Pratima>[http://pustakalaya.org/eserv.php?pid=Pustakalaya:4200&dsID=PratimaRanjit2067BS_MajipatkaRanjitkarharu.pdf Author:Pratima Ranjitkar, Article: Majipatka Ranjitkarharu, Language:Nepali]</ref>{{deadlink|date=September 2018}}<ref name=Bhairaja>[http://www.nefin.org.np//hppics/15176_Newar_RANJITKAR%201.doc Author:Professor Bhai Raja Ranjitkar, Article:Ranjitkar, Language:Nepalbhasha ]</ref> India and Pakistan |langs = [[Nepal Bhasa]],<ref name=Pratima/><ref name=Bhairaja/> [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]] and [[Marwari language|Marwari]] |rels= [[Hindu]], [[Buddhism]], [[Islam]]<ref name=Pratima/><ref name=Bhairaja/> |related= }}
The '''Chhipa''' (alternatively spelled '''Chippa''') are a community or clan of people with ancestral roots tracing back to India.
==History== [[Image:Textildruckmodel - Indien um 1900.jpg|right|thumb|A traditional stencil used to block print fabrics]]
The word ''chhipa'' is believed to come from two Nepal Bhasa words, "chhi" (to dye) and "pa" (to leave something to bask in sun).<ref name=Pratima/><ref name=Bhairaja/> According to old Gujarati record books, referred to as ''Balwa Pothy'', their [[Rajput]] community was founded in [[Nagaur]], [[Rajasthan]] and later spread to Gujarat where they took up the skill of dying and printing fabrics.{{cn|date=September 2018}}
