[[Image:Orma Village Kenya.jpg|thumb|300 px|right|Orma village in [[Tana River County]], [[Kenya]]]]
The '''Orma people''' are an ethnic community found in eastern [[Kenya]], mostly along the lower [[Tana River (Kenya)|Tana River]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=u4Q9AAAAYAAJ&dq=Orma+people&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=pastoral+people|title=Unreached Peoples of Kenya Project: Tana River report (Pokomo, Orma, Malakote, Korokoro)|last=Shingledecker|first=Ken|date=1982|publisher=Daystar Communications|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=17|language=en}}</ref> They also inhabit the Southern regions of [[Somalia]] in the [[Lower Juba]] and [[Middle Juba]] regions specifically. They are [[semi-nomadic]] shepherds, and they live in the southeastern deserts of Kenya except during the [[rainy season]], when they move their herds inland.
The Orma have a population of about 70,000 people (2005). They are related to the [[Borana Oromo people]] to the north<ref name=":0" /> and speak the [[Orma language]], a variety of [[Oromo language|Oromo]].
